ig</i> in 1016; see   Shrewsbury  ), + Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘shire, district, county’."],"variants":[{"name":"Shrewsbury","meanings":["English: habitational name from Shrewsbury (Shropshire), probably from Old English <i>scrobb</i> (genitive <i>scrobbes</i>), a variant of <i>scrubb</i>, <i>scrybb</i> ‘shrub, brushwood’, + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’."]}]},{"name":"Isolda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The name of the tragic mistress of Tristan in the Arthurian romances. There are several versions of the story. The main features are that the beautiful Isolde, an Irish princess, is betrothed to the aged King Mark of Cornwall. However, through accidentally drinking a magic potion, she and the young Cornish knight Tristan fall in love, with tragic consequences. The story has exercised a powerful hold on the European imagination. The name was relatively common in Britain in the Middle Ages, but is much rarer today."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705201,"age":114,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Isolda De Shropshire was born about 1435, in Shropshire, England. She married John Boterell. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1435–":"umbes 1435–Surnud","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","Abt 1460":"umbes 1460","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","Abt 1435":"umbes 1435","1460":"1460","1549":"1549","Aston Botterell, Shropshire, England":"Aston Botterell, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1435–":"noin 1435–Kuollut","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","1460–Male":"1460–Kuollut","1435–Female":"1435–Kuollut","Abt 1460":"noin 1460","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","Abt 1435":"noin 1435","1460":"1460","1549":"1549","Aston Botterell, Shropshire, England":"Aston Botterell, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1435–":"environ 1435–Décédée","1435–Male":"1435–Décédé","1460–Male":"1460–Décédé","1435–Female":"1435–Décédée","Abt 1460":"environ 1460","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","Abt 1435":"environ 1435","1460":"1460","1549":"1549","Aston Botterell, Shropshire, England":"Aston Botterell, Shropshire, Angleterre","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Isolda De Shropshire est née environ 1435, à Shropshire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé John Boterell. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"Abt 1435–":"um 1435–Verstorben","1435–Male":"1435–Verstorben","1460–Male":"1460–Verstorben","1435–Female":"1435–Verstorben","Abt 1460":"um 1460","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","Abt 1435":"um 1435","1460":"1460","1549":"1549","Aston Botterell, Shropshire, England":"Aston Botterell, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","lifeSummary":"Isolda De Shropshire wurde um 1435 in Shropshire, England geboren. Sie hat John Boterell geheiratet. Sie 